Cell.Text: I maintain a few contacts in other Dunmer settlements across Tamriel. | Most hail from House Redoran, but there are a few from other houses.

Most of my contacts live leagues away from Solstheim. | Sending the occasional message back and forth is all we can manage, and sometimes takes months or more to arrive. | However, any information we can glean in times like this I consider vital to House Redoran's survival.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilSourcesTLBranchTopic01: Why don't you ask them to investigate?

Cell.Text: Traitors. The lot of them. | Their collaboration with the Empire may have given them unrivaled political and economic strength, but their hearts weren't with the Dunmer people.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilHouseHlaaluTLBranchTopic: What can you tell me about House Hlaalu?

Cell.Text: Hlaalu deserved every bit of the hatred they received once the Empire released its grasp on Morrowind. | Having past ties to the Empire immediately turned them into the scapegoat for the Dunmer people's suffering.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilHouseHlaaluTLBranchTopic01: I presume that was their downfall.

Cell.Text: [S] They had welcomed the Empire with open arms, and benefited from it. | When everything was said and done, they were no longer recognized as a Great House and were dismissed from the Council.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilHouseHlaaluTLBranchTopic04: What happened to House Hlaalu as a result?

Cell.Text: Tilisu is wife to the family patriarch, Vendil. They have a single child, a daughter named Mirri. | They arrived here ten years ago, and have been nothing but a benefit to Raven Rock ever since.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilSeverinTLBranchTopic: Can you tell me more about the Severin family?

Cell.Text: They're quite wealthy and they've been quite generous by sharing their fortune with the community. | They've contributed coin, food, supplies... even helped repair a few of the buildings in town with their own hands.

People have mentioned it's a bit odd about how close in age Mirri appears to be to her father, but that's hardly a cause for alarm. | Just make sure that you find solid evidence. If I accuse them without it, I'll be the laughingstock of the colony.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilSeverinTLBranchTopic02: Nothing unusual about them at all?

Cell.Text: During the Oblivion Crisis, gates to the plane of Oblivion opened all over Morrowind. | The Empire pulled most of its forces out of Morrowind to deal with the gates in their own homeland, leaving us virtually defenseless. | We had no standing army at the time, just uncoordinated pockets of resistance.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilEmpireTLBranchTopic: Why do the Dunmer hate the Empire?

Cell.Text: House Redoran took charge and was slowly able to build an army. It took years, but it became a force to be reckoned with. | When the Argonians invaded years later, House Redoran's army was able to prevent them from sweeping across all of Morrowind. | It would be fair to say that House Redoran literally saved the Dunmer people from destruction.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilEmpireTLBranchTopic01: How did the Dunmer survive this at all?

Cell.Text: Vilur Ulen wasn't the first Ulen to live in Raven Rock. His father, Valin Ulen, was one of the first Dunmer to settle here. | Unlike his son Vilur, Valin was a good man. He contributed to the community and was quite respected. | When Valin died, his family provided the funds to construct the tomb.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilUlenTombTLBranchTopic: Why do the Ulens have a tomb in Raven Rock?

Cell.Text: The Ulen family being a part of House Hlaalu didn't matter. | It's Dunmer tradition for the ashes of the deceased to be placed in an ancestral tomb. | Valin Ulen and his son's remains were both laid to rest there because that's what he'd requested.

Node.Caption: DLC2RR02AdrilUlenTombTLBranchTopic01: But you told me House Hlaalu was disliked.
